## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` now throws at runtime on macOS — it still works on Windows and Linux.

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify legacy DSA signatures**, you have two options:

### Option A: Platform-guard DSA (keep legacy verification on Windows/Linux only)

```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA verification unavailable on macOS");

using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportParameters(legacyKey);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

### Option B: Migrate to a modern algorithm (recommended long-term)

Replace DSA with **ECDsa** or **RSA**. This requires re-signing existing data with the new key, so it's a larger effort but makes your library cross-platform and removes reliance on a legacy algorithm.

```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
var valid = ecdsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

**If you must verify existing DSA signatures on all platforms**, Option A with a platform guard is the pragmatic fix — run DSA verification only on Windows/Linux and document that macOS is unsupported for legacy DSA signature verification.
